Advantages and disadvantages of converting loans into Swiss francs
Two offers to convert loans into Swiss francs into lei have already appeared on the banking market, the main advantages being the elimination of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
The downside may come in a few years, when variable interest rates can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process of converting the loans granted by Volksbank into francs and Bancpost has announced the conversion offer for its customers.
According to data compiled by analysts of the financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers a three-year fixed interest rate of RON 1,5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, the conversion offer of Transilvania was accepted by 83% of the customers with francs due to two successive reductions: the balance with the amount of risk and administration fees paid by the customer was reduced, then an additional 22,5% reduction was applied to the LEI balance.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to what they paid monthly equivalent in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42,5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Benefits
The main advantage of the CHF loan conversion is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future franc increases and the loan will be repaid in the currency in which he receives his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no reassessment of the property, no additional guarantees and no further proof of income are required.
In practice, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the loan and no additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Both banks also offer a monthly discount rate on what customers were paying before the conversion, equivalent to lei.
The risk
The problem is that the interest rate in the first few years is mostly interest, and the customer pays very little back in principal.
The very low interest rate offer of Bancpost for the first three years seems to be advantageous for customers.
It is not known how this interest rate will develop after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be higher than 3,25%, so overall, the cost savings are lower.
A potential risk for all floating rate lending in lei is that the ROBOR index will increase significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor - CHF index).
For example, three-month ROBOR is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached 6%, in 2009 over 15% and in a few days in 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, other costs not mentioned in the initial offer may also arise.
