Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, artists, not salespeople.
The French violinist David Grimal is one of the great artists of our time, known not only as a soloist but also as the initiator of a more unusual project, quite "strange", as he calls it, Les Dissonances - an orchestra made up of international soloists and talented musicians, who perform a symphonic repertoire without a conductor, and this makes it at least a curiosity in the classical music landscape.
Les Dissonances was this year at the Enescu Festival with two performances: one on Sunday, in which the soloist was David Grimal, the orchestra's founder, and one on Monday, in which the cellist Xavier Phillips was in the foreground, the works composed by Enescu being untouched.
Both shows, performed on the Athenian stage, showed the audience a different way to interpret classical music.
Les Dissonances appeared on the music scene in 2004 being, at that time, the only classical music ensemble without a conductor.
The conductor is the most important musician for musicians.
It is true, on the one hand, that musicians need an education either to become soloists or to become performers in an orchestra - I'm talking about instrumentalists, not composers.
They are trained as 'skilled workers'.
They themselves feel they need a conductor.
On the other side of the stage, for the audience, all the musical fetishism is focused on the conductor.
And so the business, the music industry, does its marketing.
So, we're not talking about music anymore.
So if you look at this world, you have skilled workers on one side, which is stupid, and an audience that can't listen, but has to watch, which is stupid", says David Grimal.
The violinist says that this change in his music came as a result of "musical disappointments" from his solo career.
I was like a top-level athlete who had to do the same exercise all over the world with different orchestras, to make a lot of money and bring money to the music industry.
Ten years ago, when I was in my 30s, I found this very depressing, because I didn't find creativity and human brotherhood in this system.
So I found no point in going on this road.
So I decided to create Les Dissonances.
This was in 2004, and at that time nobody was doing anything like this without a conductor: "The music world, extremely conservative, didn't want these kinds of projects".
"How do you imagine marketing a collective of musicians in which there is no ego?" asks the artist.
David Grimal acknowledges that Les Dissonaces is "a luxury", stating that none of the musicians who make up the orchestra depend on the success of this project to live.
In the ensemble's 10 years of existence, the lack of a conductor has not proved to be an obstacle in the musical act: "Curiously, the more complex a repertoire we play, the simpler it seems, because all the musicians are obliged to be present in the opera and not just in the role", says Grimal, adding that at the Sunday show "we had 74 conductors on stage".
In Grimal's opinion, the Enescu Festival is "very brave", precisely because he invited Les Dissonances: "An extraordinary festival, where the biggest orchestras in the world are present and play three times a day, and in the middle of these orchestras you have also invited this strange group".
In a temple of orchestral tradition like the Enescu Festival, there is a place and interest for something different, that breaks down barriers.
