In the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide if it's time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank's boardroom, you'll see a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind Janet L. Yellen, the Fed Chair, and her colleagues that they must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Federal Reserve has been given a dual task by Congress: to maximize the U.S. employment rate and maintain price stability.
But since the Great Depression, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the X factor in an all-too-difficult decision to be announced on Tuesday that will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be unleashed by the unprecedented stimulus provided by the near-zero short-term interest rate in place since the end of 2008.
Even as most data point to a strongly growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already wary of adding volatility by raising the federal funds rate - even by a quarter of a percentage point.
Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will look at, said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
I believe, however, that if they were looking for an excuse not to raise interest rates, the increasing uncertainty in the world market is enough to give them reasons to wait further, she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is causing financial market instability.
About half of the economists recently polled by Bloomberg anticipated a rate hike this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a drop in the stock market if the Fed raises interest rates, unless policymakers mitigate the blow by promising that it would be a long time before the next hike.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep interest rates stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising if the Fed raised interest rates at this time", Lonski said.
If Fed decision makers were to do this, they would have to act deeply in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.
Other experts said that a rate hike would calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed looked set to raise rates by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected a rise in interest rates this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest rate in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed sees as total employment.
Wage earnings showed signs of increasing.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank's annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of plummeting oil prices.
The economy "can and needs to cope with higher rates given the strain on the labour market", said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to flip later this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below its May record high as investors feared that the slowing Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has receded somewhat this month, with the Dow now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed decision makers, market turmoil is added to the complex calculation of interest rate timing.
Without what's happened in financial markets and news of the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be firmer at the meeting, said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now, he predicts they'll wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the US economy and they have almost no data to build on after the events in China", Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed's major interests, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been enormous.
The mere hint by then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "tighten" monetary expansion sent shockwaves through global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected to not only monitor progress in other areas but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
Its decision-making process is "more art than science", said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at the welfare management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that the Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals.
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, a decision-making body that supported the interest rate increase, gave as an example the decisions of 1998-99.
A financial crisis that affected Asia prompted the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, despite implications for the US development that could only be identified, Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials came back on those cuts.
The Fed should only put financial stability first in a major crisis like the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate committee.
The last turbulent period is not even close to that level, he said.
"We certainly don't want to be in a situation where we fear an interest rate hike because markets are upset", said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double-mandate and does not mention financial stability and until something changes in that regard, I don't think it should take premature action.
