Weight-loss surgery could be useful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes may last for at least five years, a new study suggests.
It's still too early to tell if mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight-loss surgery than those who undergo non-surgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data", said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an obesity surgeon who wrote a paper on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight-loss surgery, also called bariatric surgery, uses various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on morbidly obese people with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
The BMI, a unit of measurement of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range 18,5-24,9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI in people who had surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI in people who received non-surgical diabetes treatment remained almost the same, at 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, 36 percent of those with diabetes were completely cured and 28 percent were partially cured.
In the medical treatment group, by comparison, only 1 percent of subjects had a complete cure and only 2 percent had a partial cure.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and LDL-C were generally better in the surgical group, the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored the blood level of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal hemoglobin A1c level is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the medically treated group, it was about 8%.
But this improved "glycemic control" - reflected in improved hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce the five-year mortality rate, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes associated with the two types of surgery.
At year five, compared with the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), had more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%) and had a higher likelihood of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona, School of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who had bariatric surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who had surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic outlook for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
This is where this paper is critical, because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group, without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when a patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
'I think we are waiting too long to urge people to take this seriously,' she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely difficult to get back to normal.
