Fourfold increase in the number of children who ingested hand detergent in the last four years
According to the Georgia Poison Control Center, poison control centers in the U.S. have reported an increase of about 400 percent since 2010 in the number of children under 12 who have swallowed hand detergent with a high alcohol content.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Control Center, hand-washing cases among children under 12 years of age reported to the center rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children have more access to these products and unfortunately, a percentage of them end up in the emergency room", Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said some children drink detergent intentionally and others do so to impress their friends or to respond to social media challenges.
You can watch videos on YouTube that show teenagers drinking detergent to create cheap drinks.
It turns out that teenagers mixed their mouthwash with alcohol to make a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the attractive smell of detergent.
"A child doesn't think it's hurting them", says Lopez.
Many of the most attractive types are scented.
Strawberry, grape, orange-flavored hand sanitizers are the most appealing to children.
Hand detergent contains approximately 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, just a few sips can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol", Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poison center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand sanitizers in accessible places, and if the little ones get to them, that's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four strawberry-scented hand-wash sprays at school, arrived at the emergency room for treatment.
She had a blood alcohol level of 179, twice the legal drinking age for an adult, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, the emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was staring and couldn't walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage as the girl fell and hit her head from alcohol, Ritchey said.
"It was scary", Nhaijah's mother, Ortoria Scott, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free wet wipes or products and to keep hand detergent out of the reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand detergent that contained an undeclared toxic ingredient.
The health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, which was specified as the active ingredient.
