The absence of similar characters in the show is obvious, given that the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, with suicide rates among young men reaching a 15-year high.
In 2013, suicide was the leading cause of death for men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more common in men than women.
In an attempt to address the issue, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, challenging the culture that prevents men from asking for help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the fight to succeed in this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if a patient is surrounded by enough friends "in a healthy mood", their chances of recovery double.
Similarly, for people who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends halves the likelihood of developing mental disorders.
Of course, for friendship to be effective, it must first be accessible.
In this era of social media-dominated communication, where the emphasis is on style rather than substance, the immediacy of the response often takes precedence over meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong, fun-loving, successful personality, even when in reality, isolation is what dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values -- our inner desire for personal growth and friendship -- that affect our mental health even more deeply.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money really can't buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was that it brought that idea to the forefront.
The characters were not defined by their jobs but by their personalities, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments of watching football in their comfortable armchairs, and Ross' passion for Rachel came from the fact that men are known to be able to associate with this situation, even if they often shy away from fully exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: ...my role in listening to suicidal and depressed people showed how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference.
Often, people who come to us don't feel able to talk to their friends.
The old saying "do it yourself" is powerful, and so is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you talk openly about your problems.
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term psychological coping mechanisms.
The show highlighted the little moments of friendship between men.
As much as objective, outward intervention over the phone helps people in desperate times, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
So if you're attending this weekend's FriendsFest hosted by Comedy Central, with full-scale filming to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends over for coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what a difference your friendship might make.
