The government approved on Wednesday the "National Immigration Strategy for 2015-2018" and the "Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage Romania is undergoing in its efforts to modernize the immigration management process on national territory", according to a press release.
The strategy aims at managing immigration effectively, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action reflecting policies set at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems faced by the States in Romania's immediate neighbourhood, measures are envisaged for the unitary and coherent management of situations arising from the possible influx of illegal immigrants into Romania, generated by crisis situations of a political, social, economic or military nature.
"The Romanian authorities will help to create a flexible admission system, but at the same time will pay special attention to citizens from countries with potential migration or that may harm national security", the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that may influence immigration and asylum, including the continuation of the conflict situation in Syria, the re-ignition of the conflict in Iraq, the continuation of an unstable situation in the areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), the continuation and intensification of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets out a number of general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, stricter controls on the legality of the stay of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the proper application of removal and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the territory of Romania for third-country nationals meeting the employment needs of the labour force, facilitating access for third-country nationals to Romanian higher education institutions for fields and professions identified as deficient.
