A date that breaks your heart.
At 20 he received a brave gift: his biological parents.
Lost in a hospital in obscure conditions in the darkness of the 1990s, when she was only two months old, small, sick and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family in Italy, in the same years when adoption was loosely regulated, a young outsider, now a beautiful blonde girl, was reunited the other day in Iași with her biological parents from a county village, after almost two decades in which no one knew anything about the others.
Crina will be 20 years old this year, and her adoptive parents in Palermo have thought of giving their beloved daughter a stunning and brave gift: a visit to Romania, to Iasi, to learn about her murky past.
The "Iasi Journal", which has been assisting the search for the family of origin after some extremely vague clues, has witnessed these meetings that practically break your heart.
The reporting, the emotions of the moments, the statements of those involved, their reactions are truly moving and overwhelming.
Crina's story begins 20 years ago in the town of Ruginoasa in the Isle of Man, when she was only two months old.
Then, because of a health problem, the girl had to be admitted to the hospital in the city.
My parents began to disagree at home, and Mother was forced to leave home.
He decided to keep the girl and send me away.
She stopped the girl, and I didn't know anything since.
"When I found out she was in the hospital, it was too late", recalls Alina, the girl's biological mother.
Crina was admitted with her grandmother to the municipal hospital in Pascani, and at the same time the girl's father, Costica Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman county.
Their lives were about to be forever separated.
They never found Crina at the hospital.
After the hospital, Crina's father went to work in another locality, and returned after six months.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iasi, and when her father returned, he could not find her.
It must have been almost nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
"She must have thought she was abandoned", relates a granddaughter of the family.
Due to financial problems, the grandmother could not come with Crina to Iasi, and the girl remained in the care of doctors.
Because no one was interested in the child's fate all this time, she was taken over by the General Directorate of Social Assistance and Child Protection of Iasi, which then gave her to the care of the Placement Center in Bucium.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were more loosely regulated than today in Romania.
At the Bucium Center she was found by Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but couldn't.
They fell in love with the blonde Crina, and after a while she would move permanently with them to Italy.
The little girl was almost two years old, the time it took for the adoption proceedings.
When I saw Crina, I felt like she was our daughter.
"It was as if my wife had given birth to her", says smiling Salvador, the adoptive father, as he grasps her frail hand in his palm.
In the country, Crina's parents, Alina and Costica, continued the search separately, each wherever they could.
The father asked the authorities in Rustinoasa, but he received no answer where his child could be.
The police then told her that she may have died, but in Iași the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I looked for her here, they told me at the court that she was in Italy, in Palermo.
And the conditions to look for her I never had.
We prayed to God that he was okay.
I thought about her all these years, but there were no ways to walk around, to find her.
"It's hard", says Crina's biological mother with tears in her eyes.
But even as the years passed, the parents in Rustinoasa were not forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past ties her to Romania.
I was a kid when I found out.
I think I was five or six.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
"I wanted to meet my parents in Romania", says Crina excitedly.
And her dream was about to come true.
In March this year, Chief Commissioner Romică Ichim, director of the Regional Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counselling Centre of Iasi, was contacted by an acquaintance in Italy, who explained to her Salvadore's desire to find Crina's biological family.
And the searches started with just one name.
Following the request we received from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
I had only one name, Balkan Costica, then the locality, Rustosa.
Soon I had a job with the town hall there, and I could ask if there was a place by the name.
They gave me some clues, only the person they found wasn't the one they were looking for.
"It took about a month to find the girl's biological father", explains Chief Commissioner Romică Ichim.
In total, it took more than three months for the authorities to find Costică and Alina, especially since each had a different home.
We started the process sometime in March, and in June and July we completed identifying the biological parents and the discussions.
"Then we decided to have a first meeting in September", Romică Ichim added.
Last weekend, Alina and Costică saw their lost face for the first time in the halls of the hospital in Iasi, 20 years ago.
The father, excited, could hardly hold back his tears, and his hands trembled incessantly.
He barely even had a word with the people around him.
A week before the date, he couldn't sleep much.
He was all excited, shaking.
"It's something to see your child after all these years", says a granddaughter, who also came with Rustinoasa's Rib.
Crina's reunion with her mother and biological brother
In conversations with his daughter, who is about to study at a prestigious university in Italy, Costica Balcan told her, among other things, that if she ever wanted to return to his village, she should come quietly: she could give him some sheep, goats, so that he could find a boy from the village and start a household.
My mother is also very emotional, she cries, and she can hardly believe that this could happen to her.
I'm really excited.
I didn't think anything like this could happen.
I've seen cases like this on TV, I've been thinking about it all these years, I've hoped, but I never thought I could be like this.
There are very high emotions.
If he could just forgive me.
I hope to visit in the future.
"I hope we can keep a bond", says Alina, Crina's mother, with tears streaming down her cheeks, while holding a napkin tightly in her hand.
She's still hiding her tears of joy in it, because she'll soon see her face again after all this bitter weather.
On the other hand, Crina, who will be 20 in just a few days, this month, is trying to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn't know what to expect, but she's sketched out a vague idea about her biological parents.
She thinks they're young, but now before the date she tries to gather her thoughts, because she has a lot to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two mothers and two fathers.
But my parents are the ones who raised me after all.
It'll be a nice meeting, a wonderful experience.
"I hope to have a good memory with them, because now there is so much to talk about", Crina confides.
First family reunion in Iasi
In the Union Square, under the early autumn sky, the family from Ruginoasa reunites their destiny with their daughter from Palermo.
Crina is 20 years old, graduating high school, following the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
It's no longer divided by borders or countries, but only by a barrier: language.
Over which, with the help of a translator, an Italian restaurant owner in the center of Iasi, they passed easily.
Those who have managed to make this meeting possible say that it is the first event of its kind ever held, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do it again.
It's the first event of its kind organized, with such an emotional charge, and I'm glad it's a success.
We at the Center have different activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with people who use drugs, people who are addicted to drugs.
But we're trying to give something good back to the society.
"If I am asked to attend another event like this, I will do it with great pleasure", says Romică Ichim, director of the Regional Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counselling Centre in Iasi, smiling.
Behind him, the Balkan family, with Crina in the middle, walk away telling their story.
They are understandable: they have a lot to say to each other.
