Corbyn, Brexit and the future of Europe
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they enjoyed in the past decades cannot continue in the years to come.
By Saturday probably few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn is.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the Labour Party in Britain, many are wondering how much we can be affected by the choice of a politician who, after all, is not in a decision-making position.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical left-wing Labour leader since the war.
An avowed Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once asked Tony Blair, then Prime Minister, to remove the royal family from Buckingham Palace), a fierce anti-American and a supporter of Vladimir Putin (he was regularly invited to comment on political events by the TV channel "Russia Today"), and of the terrorist movements Hezbollah and Hamas, he wants Britain to give up nuclear weapons and leave NATO and the EU.
For Corbyn, who at the time considered the killing of Osama bin Laden a real tragedy, ISIS is almost a favorite of the United States.
Following the pattern of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
Things like the kind of things that Tsipras said and promised in Greece until he faced the real world and the economic legality.
The new Labour leader's economic programme includes massive renationalisation and the printing of money as a solution to finance development projects and cover very generous social benefits.
Of course, some may wonder why the solution of printing money is not adopted by the whole world, we would then have a general world prosperity!
Sure, we can tax the bankers with blood, you become kind of the left's enemy of the service, but as we've seen so many times in the past, not just in the former communist states or Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of Mitterrand and Hollande's terms.
The extra sums are quickly swallowed up by the generous, uncovered promises of populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher famously observed, "The trouble with socialism is that at some point you run out of other people's money".
Few give Jeremy Corbyn any real chance of ever becoming Prime Minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in beliefs as the new party leader anyway, failed miserably in the election.
And then there was still a working class in Britain, in the classic sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were significantly more influential than they are now.
In the new industrial landscape, where services are dominant in the overall workforce and extensive automation has created a massive need for highly skilled labour in industry, Corbyn's rhetoric has limited appeal.
But even from opposition, he can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes that Corbyn's election increases the chances of Brexit, or Britain's exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership of the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that has imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric, and you look at the refugee crisis that's shaking the foundations of the EU, you get an explosive mix.
And not just for Britain.
But if the British decide to leave the Union after the referendum, which is due to take place before 2017, the symbolic loss of capital for the whole European project and the deep rifts created within it by the Euro crisis and now by refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leaves room for the most worrying scenarios.
The more so because for a whole series of member states, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which Berlin was increasingly becoming the dominant player anyway).
It is true that British business, the City, are strong advocates of the country remaining in the EU.
But today's Europe is not the same as the past.
There's a lot of resentment, which is growing in intensity even these past few weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, as we had a sample of even recently in the speech of Jean-Clude Juncker, is increasingly tending to make major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of Member States by consulting only a few European powers, mainly Germany.
And this is happening as electoral support for anti-system, anti-immigration and at the same time Eurosceptic groups is growing dramatically across the continent.
In other words, the negative emotional climate has reached a higher level than ever before.
Hence the conclusion the Financial Times draws when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on cold calculation based on the national interest.
If the voters make the brain decision, then Britain will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn's victory reminds us of the power of emotion in politics today.
However, Eastern Europe may be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as is to be expected, we see a more pronounced integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the states in the region to the periphery of the interest and decision-making in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States feed their populist rhetoric on the frustrations built up in Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in recent decades, the generous social benefits, cannot continue in the same way in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, Eurozone - immigration, both caused by hasty decisions that took into account only the political ambitions of integration, not the capacity and readiness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and may affect the situation of Romania.
And it's hard to rule anything out in terms of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are capable of dealing with such complicated situations.
